ings, Rosenberg charts an effective approach to the challenges of judging quality in works of art by analyzing master drawings from the fifteenth to twentieth centuries and comparing them with examples of followers or minor contemporaries. The result is a set of practical criteria that are applicable across diverse periods and styles. Brimming with insights from a legendary art critic and historian, On Quality in Art sheds invaluable light on drawings by artists ranging from Dürer, Raphael, Leonardo, Rubens, Rembrandt, Watteau, Degas, and van Gogh to Matisse, Picasso, and Marin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArt criticism. 0aDrawing. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  a.  aAlpers, Svetlana Leontief.  aApelles.  aApollo Belvedere (Vatican), *12.  aBelvedere Torso (Vatican).  aCimabue.  aCompany of Captain Bicker (Amsterdam).  aCézanne: Compotier, verre et pommes.  aFrancia, Francesco.  aGere, J.A.  aGiotto.  aHelst, Bartholomeus van der.  aLaocoön (Vatican).  aLippi, Fra Filippo.  aMatisse: Nude in an Armchair.  aMedici Venus (Florence), *13.  aMichelangelo.  aMountain Landscape (Cambridge, Mass.).  aMüller-Hofstede, Justus.  aNight Watch (Amsterdam).  aPollaiuolo, Antonio del.  aPool Overhung with Foliage (Les Reflets dans l'eau) (New York).  aPouncey, Philip.  aRaphael.  aSchlosser, Julius von.  aSchongauer: Head of an Oriental.  aUffizi Gallery.  aValadon: Nude Reclining.  aVasari, Giorgio.  aVermeer: Procuress.  aWoolf, Virginia.  aZeuxis.  avon Kulmbach: Studies of Men in Bondage.1 aDe Piles, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFry, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThore, Theophile, e